<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>The Fisher Effect states that a one percentage point increase in expected inflation leads to:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">A one percentage point decrease in nominal interest rates</option>
            <option letter="b">A one percentage point increase in nominal interest rates</option>
            <option letter="c">A one percentage point increase in real interest rates</option>
            <option letter="d">No change in nominal interest rates</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The Fisher Effect states that the nominal interest rate changes point-for-point with expected inflation, keeping the real interest rate constant.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>A country's balance of payments must always:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Equal zero</option>
            <option letter="b">Be in surplus</option>
            <option letter="c">Equal the trade balance</option>
            <option letter="d">Equal the capital account</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The balance of payments must always sum to zero because all international transactions have offsetting entries in either the current or capital accounts.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Automatic stabilizers work by:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Requiring congressional approval</option>
            <option letter="b">Reducing aggregate supply during recessions</option>
            <option letter="c">Automatically adjusting government spending and tax revenues</option>
            <option letter="d">Increasing interest rates during expansions</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>Automatic stabilizers like unemployment benefits and progressive taxes automatically adjust government spending and tax revenues to help stabilize the economy.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>The classical dichotomy implies that:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Money affects both real and nominal variables</option>
            <option letter="b">Money affects only nominal variables</option>
            <option letter="c">Money affects only real variables</option>
            <option letter="d">Money has no economic effects</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The classical dichotomy states that changes in the money supply affect only nominal variables (like prices) and not real variables (like output) in the long run.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
